//141. Linked List Cycle
//Given head, the head of a linked list, determine if the linked list has a cycle in it.
//Return true if there is a cycle in the linked list. Otherwise, return false.
//Example 1:
//Input: head = [3,2,0,-4], pos = 1
//Output: true
//Example 2:
//Input: head = [1,2], pos = 0
//Output: true
//Example 3:
//Input: head = [1], pos = -1
//Output: false


Brute Force Approach -> (Hash Set)
class Solution {
public:
    bool hasCycle(ListNode *head) {
        unordered_set<ListNode*> visited;
        ListNode* curr = head;
        while(curr) {
            if(visited.count(curr)) {
                return true;
            }
            visited.insert(curr);
            curr = curr->next;
        }
        return false;
    }
};

Intuition ->
// Store visited nodes, not values.
// If the same node is reached again, a cycle exists.
Traverse the linked list.
For every node:
Check whether we've already visited it.
If yes:
Cycle exists.
Otherwise:
Store it in the hash set and continue.

Complexity Analysis ->
Time Complexity -> O(n)
where:
n = number of nodes
Reason:
Each node is visited at most once.

Space Complexity -> O(n)
Reason:
Hash set stores visited nodes.

Optimal Approach -> (Floyd's Cycle Detection Algorithm)

class Solution {
public:
    bool hasCycle(ListNode *head) {
        ListNode* slow = head;
        ListNode* fast = head;
        while(fast && fast->next) {
            slow = slow->next;
            fast = fast->next->next;
            if(slow == fast) {
                return true;
            }
        }
        return false;
    }
};

Intuition ->
Use two pointers:
slow → moves 1 step
fast → moves 2 steps
If a cycle exists:
Fast eventually catches slow.
If no cycle exists:
Fast reaches NULL.

Complexity Analysis ->
Time Complexity -> O(n)
where:
n = number of nodes
Reason:
Both pointers traverse the list at most once.

Space Complexity -> O(1)
Reason:
Only two pointers are used.

